# Personal use only

Luma is a **personal daily-driver** Rust CLI/TUI: a keyboard-first workbench for local modules and
personal information. Do **not** optimize for public release, distribution, notarization,
multi-user product, or marketing.

Codex and Claude Code are references for TUI ergonomics only — prompt editing, keyboard
discoverability, previews, command surfaces, and clear feedback. Luma is **not an AI-agent
product**: do not adopt conversational chat, LLM integration, autonomous planning/execution, or
tool-orchestration workflows.

## Do

- Keep the currently registered modules solid for local use: Apps, Windows, Proxy, Clipboard,
  Notes, Quicklinks, Snippets, Wordbook, Records, Projects, Command Recipes, SSH, Timers, and
  Secrets. The Fake module is test/demo-only and default-off.
- Prefer small fixes for real friction over roadmap/checklist completion.
- Follow `rust/docs/GOVERNANCE.md` for inventory sync, layering, honest states, and soft file-size
  triggers.
- Persist only under LumaNext (`LUMA_NEXT_*` in tests).
- Use structured unavailable / permission / not-configured outcomes (no silent fake success).
- Keep `rust/bins/luma/src/compose.rs` as the sole module/adapters registration root.
- Keep TUI update/reducer and render pure; effects own I/O and async work.
- Use `/` for every interactive module/local command (`/ssh`, `/rec browse`, `/settings`); bare
  or colon-prefixed command forms are retired and unprefixed input is global search.
- When adding a module, prefer a module-local implementation plus ports/adapters, one compose
  registration, contract tests, and documentation. Avoid central engine/reducer/render edits;
  treat unavoidable central branching as an extensibility cost.

## Do not

- Add CI release gates, cargo-deny-as-policy, long soak/PTY evidence packs, or notarization/TCC matrices “for release”.
- Build Web / native GUI / Tauri / Electron / agent daemon / plugin ABI.
- Add AI/LLM chat, autonomous agents, task planners, tool-execution loops, or background and
  multi-session agent orchestration unless the user explicitly changes the product boundary.
- Revive deferred stubs (Window layouts, Menu search, Browser tabs) or signed-host Translate —
  keep them out of tree. (`luma.windows` list+focus is allowed — not Window layouts.
  `luma.wordbook` vocab/SRS is allowed.)
- Treat architecture purity (adapter moves, crate splits) as mandatory unless it unblocks personal use.

## Audit expectations

For a full audit, inspect architecture, all registered modules, business flows, TUI state and
stale async results, docs, code smells, memory/task/FFI lifetimes, concurrency/cancellation,
shutdown and crash recovery, migrations, security/privacy, performance/backpressure, CLI/JSON
compatibility, extensibility, and test quality. Findings require severity, confidence, absolute
file/line evidence, trigger, impact, root cause, suggested direction, and a regression test.
Do not modify files during a first audit pass.

## Verify (enough for personal)

```bash
cd rust
cargo fmt --all -- --check
cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings
cargo test --workspace --all-features
cargo test -p luma --test cli_blackbox
./scripts/check_architecture.sh
```
